BEHIND THE SCENES

Pride, Gratitude and Nostalgia fill me up equally as I watch this video!
As a show stylist the job brief was putting together looks for 7 episodes, a couple open mics, the grand finale & a Giant Cold Open. 
And this involved 2 Hosts, 4 Judges, 7 mentors, 8 Contestants, 6500 challenges and 8290 unforseen panic situations.

Guess what? Ticked all the boxes!

Immense Love and Gratitude to my Army: @komaljain1112 @shreya_jainn_
@home_grownstylist
@tejashreeraul
@thestylesetter_
Thank you for keeping up with the same energy!

A Big Big shoutout to @kreetigogia @beingtulsyan and every single member of the incredible cast & crew that made this show super successful despite 3 lockdowns & a myriad of challenges.

Can't thank @shriyaagrawal01 @lesiyaapa
enough for the flawless coordination through out with the costume team. Bahut shukriya!

#Love

𝘍𝘢𝘯𝘬𝘢𝘢𝘳 •  फ़नकार •  فَن کار 

As a designer, this is one of the best feelings I get to experience. To make an outfit that starts literally from plain raw white fabric into the most important garment of a bride's life!

I rarely work with ready fabric. The emotion of making something so precious out of nothing is unparalleled. It's exhilarating.
It's an all consuming job. Days of labour. 30-45 days depending on the job at hand. Visualising, Planning , Discussion, changes, trials, the back and forth to create the ultimate. 
And the outcome is the combined effort of every single artisan involved. I work with magicians. I stand in awe on days when my dyer understands the color that's literally in my head and he knows how to deliver. 
What I enjoy the most is walking into the embroiders workshop and watch them at thier creative best while they cope with the pressure of adhering to the deadline. A group of Karigars, sitting around the khaat (𝘸𝘰𝘰𝘥𝘦𝘯 𝘧𝘳𝘢𝘮𝘦 𝘸𝘩𝘦𝘳𝘦 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘧𝘢𝘣𝘳𝘪𝘤 𝘪𝘴 𝘢𝘵𝘵𝘢𝘤𝘩𝘦𝘥)
humming songs in their mother tongue sometimes, blasting Bollywood music on days and reciting prayers on the other.
And adding love to every stitch on that fabric.

Amidst all this, the bride's largest contribution is to trust someone entirely with this responsibility and giving them the creative liberty to express. 
Thank you @rutujamoray ❤️

latestPosts.caption:
What if there was a toolbox for love?

At Spoken Fest Mumbai 2025, Amrita Saluja brings us a beautifully honest poetic performance—Love Ka Toolbox—about how we build, break, and rebuild relationships. Through her signature blend of warmth and truth, Amrita unpacks the tools we need for love: communication, patience, foundation, repair, and most of all, understanding.

With tenderness and resonance of Hindi & Punjabi spoken word poetry, this piece will stay with anyone who’s ever loved deeply and tried to make it work.

Full video out on YouTube now!

Music by: Aditya Bhandakkar
Shot by: Slip Disc Films
Edited by: Shannon Maben

#SpokenFestMumbai2025 #AmritaSaluja #SpokenFest #KommuneIndia #Storytelling #HindiStorytelling #Poetry #HindiPoetry #LovePoetry #SpokenWord #SpokenWordPoetry #Kavita #PoetryHindi #punjabipoetry

हम यहाँ पहुंच ही गए ❤️

Just like that, it has been a year,
Of standing on stage with a full heart, of sharing stories that carry pieces of me and of believing in love in all its forms.
It all began in a small living room among friends and somehow found its way to hundreds of strangers who listen with vulnerable hearts and show up with so much love.
Thank you for sharing home with these words!

मेरा साहस बढ़ाने के लिए शुक्रिया!
Am grateful, overwhelmed and supremely excited for what's coming!

A Woman’s Strength is in the Stories She Wears and the Words She Weaves🩷

This Women’s Day, we celebrate Amrita Saluja—a poet and stylist who embodies the power of self-expression. Through her verses, she gives voice to emotions that often go unspoken. Through her style, she curates identity, confidence, and individuality.

But her strength isn’t just in her creativity—it’s in the relationships that inspire her and the sisterhood that walks beside her.
